@node REQUIREMENTS "Requirements"

@{b}REQUIREMENTS@{ub}

  o An Amiga computer or emulator with Kickstart 2.0 or later.
  o A 68020+ CPU.  Emulation WILL NOT WORK on a 68000 system!
  o 512k free RAM (preferably most of it FAST RAM).
  o ASL library for the file requesters.

@endnode


@node DESCRIPTION "Description"

@{b}DESCRIPTION@{ub}

AmiTRS80 emulates the Tandy Radio Shack TRS-80 home computer, one of
the original home micros introduced in the late 1970s along with
Commodore's PET and the Apple ][.
 
As far as we are aware, AmiTRS80 is the only TRS-80 Model 1 emulator
for Amiga computers. At present it emulates the following configuration:-

	o Z80 CPU (including some undocumented instructions)
	o TRS-80 Model 1 keyboard at the hardware level
	o 48K RAM
	o Load "/CMD" and execute, directly from AmigaDOS
	o Write protection for the ROM area
	o Virtual cassette support

Updates for version 1.0:

	o Loading of /BAS program files extracted from disk images
	o System-friendly allocation of any audio channel (or none)
	o Speed control from the keyboard, tooltypes or command-line
	o Volume control from the keyboard, tooltypes or command-line
	o Speed, volume and error-message display 
	o Low priority (-1) Z80 task defers to system-friendy operations
	o Z80 core source compatible with DEVPAC 3 as well as PHXASS
	o Fast variant (with no speed limiter) for slower Amigas
	o Improved documentation (you're reading it)

Still in the pipeline: (if there is sufficient interest in the project)

	o Loading and saving of memory snapshots
	o Up to 80 track single-sided disk drives (maybe double density)
	o Printer port output directed to an Amiga device or disk file
	o Serial Port redirection

The emulation runs in a reasonably system-friendly manner, multitasking
properly with other programs. It does, however, bypass graphics library
calls in favour of directly writing to its own screen's Bitmap.
This was done primarily for speed reasons. This may or may not be
compatible with third party graphics cards. It has been tried on a
PICASSO 2 and worked fine.

@endnode


@node WHY "Why A TRS-80 Model 1 Emulator?"

@{b}WHY A TRS-80 Model 1 EMULATOR?@{ub}

Primarily it was the first computer that I (Red Skull) owned. I remember the thrill
of getting my Level 1 4K machine home for the first time early in 1978. It was miles
ahead of the single-board 6502 machine I had been playing with up to that point.

Secondly I feel that it is much easier for a beginner to create a working program
on one of these old 8-bit machines than on one of today's super-powered 
(by comparison) home computers. Just look at the myriad compile options on any
of today's C-compilers!

Thirdly, a lot of the old software is really worthwile, despite the graphics 
limitations, and addictive to play.

Last but not least because I envied the IBM-PC crowd having a Model 1 emulator!

Simon Goodwin is responsible for the updates from version 0.9 to 1.0.
He piled in having written hundreds of articles on and about his
1980-vintage TRS-80 clone, a Video Genie made by EACA, and after writing
a series of articles about emulators for Amiga Format magazine, restoring
a couple of real Video Genies, and wishing to run those old programs on
his Amiga 4000.

@endnode


@node RUNNING "Running the Emulation"

@{b}RUNNING THE EMULATION@{ub}

Double click on the AmiTRS80 icon or run it from a shell. The
@{" Parameters and tooltypes " link CONFIG} page explains the
optional startup settings, but the defaults are a good start.

Red Skull reckons the gadgets are pretty self-explanatory. But
Simon has decided to explain them anyway, as if you find them
obvious you'll probably not be reading this, unless you like
reading or are curious anyway.


@{b}QUIT@{ub}

This closes down the emulator and releases all resources.

There is a one-second delay before the screen closes, to ensure
that the separate Z80 task is out of the way before the rug is
pulled from under it.

@{b}RESET@{ub}

RESET is the equivalent of pressing the button at the back of the
TRS-80 keyboard. It generates a non-maskable interrupt. This does
not generally clear the program from memory but gets you back to
the BASIC READY prompt. Sometimes it will not be possible to load
or run further programs because the memory contents prevent this
(e.g. after running large complex programs like Avalon Hill's
Computer Diplomacy).

In such a case, enter SYSTEM then enter /0 to cold-start the TRS-80
- (0 is the address of the start of the ROM, where execution starts
when the machine is switched on).

@{b}LOAD/CMD@{ub}

This loads and runs a /CMD code file, or prints a message in the
lower right corner of the screen if the file selected does not
start with the correct data (a '5' byte followed by sections of
code to be loaded, encoded with their length and address).

You need to press Enter (or specify an upper memory address) at the
initial memory size prompt before loading a CMD file, so that the
TRS-80 memory map is configured when the CMD program starts to run.

The emulator loads /CMD disk files but does not support disk file
access; so press Help, equivalent to the TRS-80 Clear key, to skip
the high-score load and save stage on Big Five games, for instance.

You can configure the directory where AmiTRS80 looks for CMD files
first, as explained on the @{" Configuration " link CONFIG} page.

@{b}LOADCASS@{ub}

LOADCASS selects a CAS cassette image file, or a /BAS file containing
BASIC tokens from a TRS-80 disk file. In the latter case the program
should be written in Level 2 BASIC, rather than the extended disk BASIC,
unless you've loaded LEVEL3 or LEVEL4 extensions. Disk-specific commands
and functions will not work as the emulation does not support DOS calls.
However support for /BAS files is enough to run most of the programs
available online, including Android Nim, Beewary, Dancing Demon etc.
(look for LANCE.ZIP online for this collection, among many others).

In either case you need to type an appropriate command to load the
'tape' into the emulator. BASIC programs, in /BAS or CAS format,
are loaded with CLOAD. Machine code programs are loaded by typing
SYSTEM then entering the first character of the tape code name.

In general, to start a BASIC program after loading, type RUN. To
start a code file type / and press Enter when the SYSTEM prompt
re-appears. Some programs of each type will auto-run.

You can configure the initial path for CAS files, as explained
on the @{" Configuration " link CONFIG} page.

@{b}SAVECASS@{ub}

This allows you to select a file to which subsequent cassette
output (e.g. from CSAVE and PRINT #-1 commands) will be sent.
The file works like a virtual cassette tape. After such output
the file can be selected with LOAD CAS and the output can be
loaded back from the file as if it was a real tape. The position
of the tape is reset to 0, the start, when you select a new one
with LOADCASS or SAVECASS.

To extend an existing tape file you need to load it, select it
or (safer) another, with SAVECASS, re-save the initial content
you've just loaded, and carry on writing the new data at the
end.

There is a limit of 64K for the virtual cassette buffer. When
you load a CAS file the number of bytes in it is displayed at
the end of the last line of the emulator screen.

You can configure the initial path for CAS files, as
the @{" Configuration " link CONFIG} page explains.

@endnode


@node KEYBOARD "Keyboard Mapping"

@{b}KEYBOARD MAPPING@{ub}

The Keyboard of AmiTRS80 corresponds (pretty much) to the keys of the Amiga.

The <HELP> key is the equivalent of the TRS-80 <CLR> key.
The <DEL> key is the equivalent of the TRS-80 <BREAK> key.

Both Left and Right <SHIFT> keys are read as a LEFT <SHIFT> by the Z80 routines.

One slight problem exists with selection of shifted key combinations.

If a shifted key combination is pressed and the <SHIFT> key is released FIRST,
then that key's ordinary function cannot be accessed until the previously
shifted combination is again selected and the <SHIFT> key released LAST.

This shouldn't cause any problems, just be aware if certain key combinations
don't seem to work this is probably why.

Four Amiga function keys are used to adjust the emulation speed and audio volume.

@{b}SPEED DELAY@{ub}

Press F1 to increase and F2 to decrease the delay between instructions.
See  @{" Speed Regulation  " link SPEED} for more details.

@{b}SOUND@{ub}

Press F3 and F4 to adjust the volume of sound effects, if the emulator
has allocated an audio channel for direct sound output. For more information
see @{" Sound Effects " link SOUND}.

@endnode


@node SOUND "Sound effects"

@{b}SOUND EFFECTS@{ub}

Sound effects are derived from output to the TRS-80 cassette port (port 255)
as that is how most TRS-80 games generated sound - mostly clicks and beeps,
though there was a fashion for rudimentary but recognisable sampled speech.

The alternative and hardware-destroying technique of rattling the
cassette motor control relay to make noises is not emulated. ;-)
This used to result in welded-up contacts on the real computer,
but there's no such relay on an Amiga, and if there was you'd
probably not want to burn it out.

@{b}Audio Channels@{ub}

The emulator can use any one of the four Amiga audio channels to replay
sound effects generated by TRS-80 software. By default audio channel 2
is allocated, leaving 0 and 1 free as a stereo pair for system-hostile
programs such as module players that bang the metal without allocating
it first. If channel 2 is not available the emulator attempts to allocate
channel 3, then 0, then 1, unless the parameter SILENT is supplied as a
tooltype or on the command line, in which case the emulator runs with
no sound.

If a channel is allocated it remains dedicated to the TRS-80 till the
emulation is quitted. This is necessary because the Z80 task may try
to use the channel at any time if the program it runs attempts to
access the original hardware, and because the Z80 core is written
to run as fast as possible.

@{b}Volume control@{ub}

Whichever channel is allocated to the task, you can adjust its volume
from 0 (silent) to 16 (loudest) in steps of roughly 2 dB by pressing
Amiga function keys F3 and F4 while the emulation runs. The new volume
level is displayed in the middle of the bottom line of the emulator
screen.

The initial volume can be set to any value in the range 0 (silent,
but with a channel allocated in case you decide to press F3 to fase
it up later) to 16 with the VOLUME= icon tooltype or a parameter
VOLUME= on the command line:

e.g. 

	AmiTRS80 volume=2

the case of the argument or tooltype is irrelevant, so you could type
Volume= or VOLume= or VOLUME=, but the equals sign is essential.

@{b}Sound limits@{ub}

You may have several versions of the emulator, each using different
channels, or none, running on a single computer. However the sound
from each will be choppy as the system will have to share time between
all the emulations, so you'll hear a fraction of a second of sound
from each, in round-robin sequence.

Aminet programs such as QUANTUM (or a simple poke with PEEK+POKE)
can make this smoother by reducing the amount of time between task
swaps, but you still should not expect several emulations to play
smoothly in harmony. QUANTUM 1 is the best you'll get, swapping
between tasks every ten or 20 milliseconds.

@endnode


@node SPEED "Speed Regulation"

@{b}SPEED REGULATION@{ub}

This slows down the emulator to run at a more realistic speed on fast
68030, 68040 and (especially) 68060 systems. A delay of about 150 gives
authentic performance on a 50 MHz 68060 system. On a 68020 or low-spec
68030 the emulation will probably run slower than a real TRS-80 and a
delay of 0 will deliver the best results you can expect. A 68030 at
40 MHz with typical SIMM RAM delivers an authentic 1.79 MHz with the
minimum DELAY. If you're lucky and desperate for speed, you may find
a version with no speed limiting - as even a delay of zero imposes
some overhead - in your archive, with a name like AmiTRS80fast. This
has no speed control and just runs as fast as the host will let it.

Since the Z80 core takes all the CPU time the host can give it - at
any DELAY setting - the emulations runs at a priority of -1 so that
Workbench and system-friendly programs, that wait when they've done
all that they urgently need to do, take priority over the CPU-hungry
emulation.

The initial delay can be set to any value in the range 0 (as fast
as possible) to 32767 (a few Z80 Kilohertz, at best) with the
DELAY= icon tooltype or a parameter DELAY= on the command line:

e.g. 

    AmiTRS80 delay=20

When the emulator is running you can adjust this delay in real-time
by pressing the Amiga function keys F1 and F2. The current value is
displayed at the bottom of the screen, in the lower left corner.

@endnode


@node ROMIMAGE "Rom Image?"

@{b}Obtaining a ROM IMAGE@{ub}

We dont need no steenking Rom Images...

AmiTRS80 has its own MODIFIED inbuilt image. For details of some of
the changes see {" this " link CASSETTE} page.

@endnode


@node CASSETTE "Virtual Cassette Operation"

@{b}VIRTUAL CASSETTE@{ub}

A 64k buffer is set aside for the Virtual Cassette. Virtual Cassette files need
to be brought into the buffer before they are visible to AmiTRS80, just like putting
a cassette into the recorder.

The LOADCASS gadget allows you to load a cassette file into the buffer, effectively
destroying the previous contents. Then use the CLOAD or SYSTEM commands from BASIC
to "read" the cassette.

Similarly SAVECASS saves the currently used portion of the buffer out to disk.
Using the same filename as a previously saved cassfile will over-write that file.

By "currently used" I mean that if you have CSAVE'D a program that would only be 6k
long then only that portion of the buffer is saved.

If you CSAVE twice before saving the buffer out to AMIGADOS, then the first program
CSAVE'D will be LOST! 

AmiTRS80 operates the cassette by using three currently undefined Z80 instructions.

	ED01 - writes the A register to the cass buffer and increments the buffer pointer.
	ED02 - reads the A register from the current buffer location and increments
	       the buffer pointer.
	ED03 - rewinds the tape (resets the buffer pointer to 0000).

The relevant cassette routines in the inbuilt ROM image have been patched to use these
instructions:

	$0235 - CSIN  - read the A reg from cassette.
	$0264 - CSOUT - write the A reg to cassette.
	$0287 - CSHWR - write the cass header
	$0296 - CSHIN - find the header info on the tape.

All programs that use the ROM routines to read/write cassette data should work fine.

Unpredictable results will occur if you Load/Save a cassfile while the TRS-80
side is in the process of a CLOAD or CSAVE.

There's more information about the control gadgets @{" here " link RUNNING}.

@endnode


@node TECH "Program Information"

@{b}PROGRAM INFORMATION@{ub}

AmiTRS80 is written in a mixture of C and 68020 Assembler.

SAS 6.58 (Yep! still being supported, you can't keep a good program team down)
and PHXass (freeware) were used in development, with CED V3.5 and Devpac 3.18
the editors of choice. This guide was validated by AGuideCheck, free on Aminet.

Gadget handling, program loading and saving, and keyboard emulation are in C.
The Z80 emulator and the screen write routines are written in assembler and
run as a separate process.

The Z80 core uses an "instruction pipelining" system, not dissimilar to that
used in the excellent "APPLE2000" by Kevin Kralian. While tending to be rather
memory-hungry, speed-wise it is very efficient.

ASL.library is used for the file requesters as nothing elaborate was required
on the single-bitplane TRS-80 screen.

The Z80 HALT instruction will currently terminate program operation.

Compiling your own version from the included source:

All you need to compile from the SAS/C editor is included in the SRC directory.

Once you have compiled the executable you must make one slight ZAP.

Load up the executable with your favourite binary editor and ZAP the longword
at file offset $18

from 00000C00  -> 00008000

This sets aside some DX.L space for the cassette buffer.

If you wan't to create a Model3 version just change the SCOPTIONS to include
"rom3.o" instead of "rom.o"

Then zap offset $18  00000E00 -> 00008000

We haven't patched the Model3 ROM for virtual cassette operation yet. That may
appear in a future release.

The Z80.ASM source can be assembled with Devpac 3 or a recent version of the
free PHXASS. Please see the comments in the source for more details, and if
you're still baffled contact @{" the authors " link SHARE} for advice.

The symbols MONITOR and LIMITER in the C source and corresponding equates in
the assembly code control the generation of Z80 trace and speed control code;
it is essential to make sure that values defined in the C are non-zero
in the linked assembler. You can potentially make four versions of the
emulator by permuting combinations of these two symbols.


@{b}Tools@{ub}

The Tools directory contains source and object code for programs used to
test and develop the AmiTRS80 user-interace.

@endnode


