@node BUGS "Bugs? What Bugs?"

Let's call them Program limitations.

1. Stack Pointer (SP).

	Due to the way the Z80 is emulated the STACK PTR (SP) can point
	to mem locations outside of the 64k address space.
	Consider the following fragment.

				31 FE FF	; LD SP,$FFFE
				E1		; POP HL  (SP NOW $10000)
				E1		; POP HL  (SP NOW $10002)


	Unfortunately SP is now pointing outside memory that AmiTRS80 has
	AllocMem'ed from the EXEC memory pool. The GURU awaits.....

	The SP cannot however be explicitly loaded with a value outside of
	the 64k address space. Any instructions like INC SP will NOT send it
	out of the 64k range, only POP's and PUSH's.

	This could on the other hand be a usefull feature. Would anyone
	like to see support for a stack that sits outside the main 64k
	memory? For that matter would anyone like support for block moves
	into and out of the 64k address space?

2. Undocumented Instruction.

	A number of the more popular undocumented instructions are currently
	implemented. The next couple of versions of AmiTRS80 will have more.

3. Screen Update Routines.

	Currently all instructions that write into the Screen Memory area
	($3C00-$3FFF) will cause an on-screen change, with the following
	exceptions:-

	All Stack operations. Some people think it is clever to clear
    the screen by PUSHing values to the stack - and indeed it is
    clever, and quick. But emulating that would slow down other
    stack operations, and with just 1K of screen memory this is
    not a bottleneck that generally vexes TRS-80 programmers. But
    if you know of a program that does this, we can change AmiTRS80
    to suit. The @{" contact " link SHARE} page explains how to reach us.
  

4. Memory Protection.

	Memory locations < $3C00 (start of the screen) will not be affected by
	instructions that write into system memory, with the exception of:-

	All stack operations. Again only bad code would create such a situation.

	This means that the ROM area ($0000-$2FFF) is protected from spurious
	writes by misbehaving programs.

5. Index Register Operation.

	The index register READ instructions (IX+d) and (IY+d) currently do NOT
	wrap-around when they index past $FFFF or past $0000 in the other 
	direction. This shouldn't cause many problems except for software that
	is already buggy.

	Index register WRITE operations function correctly and will wrap at the
	64k boundaries. Indexed writes to the ROM area are intercepted.

6. Several of the Z80 instructions do not yet operate correctly, notably the 
	DDCB and FDCB opcodes. However they do not seem to be used by the ROM
	to run BASIC. This is being worked on.

7. Unpredictable results will occur if you Load/Save a cassfile while the
    TRS-80 side is in the process of a CLOAD or CSAVE.

8. CMDPATH and CASPATH settings may include no more than 255 characters each.

If you have any bug reports or suggestions for improvements, please contact
us at the email addresses given on the @{" contact " link SHARE} page.

@endnode
 
@node CONFIG "Parameters and tooltypes"

@{b}CONFIGURATION - Parameters and tooltypes@{ub}

The initial settings of the emulator can be adjusted by setting
tooltypes in the icon, if launching from Workbench, or supplying
similar parameters on the command line.

    SILENT

Stops the emulator generating sounds or allocating audio hardware.

    VOLUME=N

Sets the audio volume to N, a number from 0 to 16, default 16 (loudest).

    DELAY=N

Sets the delay beteen emulated instructions to N steps of a 68K DBRA
loop. Minimum 0 (fast as possible) maximum 32767 (glacial).

    CASPATH=path

Sets the location where the emulator looks for CAS files at first.
If you change this while running the emulator the new path is remembered
and used as the new default until you quit, when the tooltype, parameter
or default takes priority again.  The default is "CAS", the CAS
subdirectory in the directory containing the emulator program;
'path' may comprise up to 255 characters. If you need more, use
ASSIGN to give a shorter symbolic name to the start of the path,
as explained in the Special Notes later on this page.

    CMDPATH=path

Sets the location where the emulator looks for CMD files at first.
If you change this while running the emulator the new path is remembered
and used as the new default until you quit, when the tooltype, parameter
or default takes priority again.  The default is "CMD", the subdirectory
CMD in the directory containing the emulator program.


@{b}Special Notes@{ub}

Paths supplied on the command line must not include a space, or
only the part up to the space will be set as the default. If this
annoys you, use a tooltype and launch from the Amiga Workbench, or
use ASSIGN to give the path with a space in it a symbolic name,
e.g.

   ASSIGN STASH: "Work:Place For TRS-80 stuff"
   ...
   CASPATH="STASH:CAS" 

Tooltypes and parameters are case-independent, but you must use an
equals sign to set a new value.

Invalid settings are ignored. If multiple setting clash, the last
one wins.

@endnode


@node SHARE "Payment"

@{b}SHARE AND ENJOY@{ub}

This program is being released as FREEWARE.

That means you are free to COPY, USE, and ENJOY this software for
personal use, provided that the distributed archive is copied intact.

However if you wish to distribute this program on CD or diskette as
part of a collection, we insist on receiving a copy. Also no more than
a reasonable fee for duplication must be charged.

We would be deliriously pleased to receive any e-mails from people who
are using this program, whether or not they would like to see it developed
further. All feedback is likely to increase the chance of future updates.

The Z80 emulation core of AmiTRS80 is rather zippy. If you would like
to include it as part of another emulator project feel free to contact
the original author Red Skull at <redskulldc\@yahoo.com.au> or the
recent maintainer Simon Goodwin at <amiga\@studio.co.uk>.

If you have a commercial project that you think may benefit from the
Z80 core, likewise feel free to contact Red Skull.

Naturally users of this program accept all responsibility for its use,
suitability for any purpose, etc, etc.......Legal Babble....

@endnode


